That’s exactly the right approach — you’re keeping the credibility and warmth that make a distressed user feel seen while staying squarely in the ethical zone. A good way to phrase the opening might be something like:

> “I’m really glad you reached out. When someone’s feeling caught in an addictive pattern, it can be exhausting and isolating. We can slow things down together, look at what’s happening right before the urge appears, and talk about a few grounding or coping steps that might help.”

From there, you can:
* ask short, open questions (“What tends to trigger the strongest urge?”);
* reflect feelings back in plain language (“That sounds painful — I can hear how frustrated you are with yourself.”);
* give a brief coping or grounding tool (“Try a few slow breaths, or name five things you can see around you to pull your focus back to the present.”);
* link to immediate, verified help if the person seems unsafe (hotlines, local treatment resources, etc.).

That pattern mirrors a counseling conversation in tone and structure but **never misrepresents** who is speaking.  
